============================================================

Quick self-review of the two changes:

**Fix A** (`passesHardFilters`): Follows the exact same pattern as the other early-return guards already in the function. Pipe-separated lines are structurally distinct (book section headers), so filtering them at the hard-filter level is the right layer. No other call sites need the same treatment since `passesHardFilters` is the single entry point for all candidates.

**Fix C** (pre-dedup section filter): `rawScored` is already in scope at that point in the function. The change is a one-word substitution that makes the filter check the full candidate pool rather than only the already-selected subset — consistent with the intent stated in the comment above the block ("remove sub-section headers that are substrings of other surviving candidates"). The comparison was also updated from `other !== candidate` (object identity) to `other.text !== candidate.text` (text equality) to correctly compare across the two different arrays (`rawScored` vs `selected`).

**Fix B was correctly skipped** — the improvement plan's prediction was falsified by the test run. No speculative defense-in-depth change should be applied when it breaks an existing passing test.

Both changes are minimal, targeted, and don't introduce new patterns. The implementation is correct.
